00:00:00.659 --> 00:00:03.670
&gt;&gt;presenter: I'm gonna keep the introduction
short because he's a super interesting guy

00:00:03.670 --> 00:00:08.860
and I'd like to get him on the mic sooner.
But just briefly, he's a Dominican American

00:00:08.860 --> 00:00:13.339
writer; he lived in Jersey after moving here
with his family around age six. Just from

00:00:13.339 --> 00:00:16.620
talking to him, I learned that he worked in
a steel mill and, I think, probably a lot

00:00:16.620 --> 00:00:20.869
of other things. If you haven't checked out
his first short story collection, it's called

00:00:20.869 --> 00:00:24.880
"Drown". It's super excellent. And his newest
novel, which hopefully you have a copy of,

00:00:24.880 --> 00:00:33.200
got rave review from Michiko Kakutani in The
New Yorker and an excerpt of it was illustrated

00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:39.480
by one of the Hernandez brothers--famous cartoonists.
He also wrote this really, I read this really

00:00:39.480 --> 00:00:43.629
great story in NPR's, "This American Life"--
I thought it was hilarious-- called "How to

00:00:43.629 --> 00:00:49.050
Date a Browngirl, Blackgirl, Whitegirl or
Halfie" and he also teaches undergrad creative

00:00:49.050 --> 00:00:54.410
writing at MIT. And the last thing I'd like
to say is that if you open your book, the

00:00:54.410 --> 00:01:00.289
epigraph to the book is from The Fantastic
Four comic book: "Of what import are brief,

00:01:00.289 --> 00:01:06.520
nameless lives...to Galactus?" It's probably
the best epigraph I've ever seen. Please welcome

00:01:06.520 --> 00:01:08.520
Junot Diaz.

00:01:08.520 --> 00:01:11.520
&gt;&gt;Diaz: Thank you.

00:01:11.520 --> 00:01:12.520
[applause]

00:01:12.520 --> 00:01:19.840
Guys, thanks so much for coming out here.
It's kind of a cool thing and I really don't

00:01:19.840 --> 00:01:28.200
know what the actual details of it are, but
it's really kind of a wonderful thing that

00:01:28.200 --> 00:01:33.620
the, that they give you these kind of little
events, yeah? And for me, it's just like--

00:01:33.620 --> 00:01:39.270
I'm always kind of astonished and humbled
when anybody will take any time from their

00:01:39.270 --> 00:01:46.580
lunch break to come talk to an artist or interact
with an artist or some kind of writer or anything

00:01:46.580 --> 00:01:53.160
like that. So, I find that to be extraordinarily
human and touching. So, thank you for taking

00:01:53.160 --> 00:02:00.330
a little bit of time. It's hard to make any
time for anything, so this is like, I honestly

00:02:00.330 --> 00:02:04.850
just can't believe it, so thanks so much.
And it's sorta weird, I have this year off.

00:02:04.850 --> 00:02:10.530
I'm not teaching at my school; MIT. And so
I have these bizarre pangs when I'm walking

00:02:10.530 --> 00:02:17.240
around your campus because it's like the same
architect who built the damn MIT and built

00:02:17.240 --> 00:02:23.700
this place? You know? It's like, just the
numbered buildings and your signs don't work.

00:02:23.700 --> 00:02:27.890
Which is like MIT. My students always change
all the signs. So, they're like, "Building

00:02:27.890 --> 00:02:33.740
41; it'll actually be the opposite direction."
So, I felt like, "Aww. God, this place is

00:02:33.740 --> 00:02:36.260
equally fucked up. I think it's cool."

00:02:36.260 --> 00:02:37.260
[laughter]

00:02:37.260 --> 00:02:42.420
So, thanks guys. And since we're-- I hope
you guys don't mind, we're like an intimate

00:02:42.420 --> 00:02:48.240
group, if I like talk more like I would normally
talk and not how I would talk with my students?

00:02:48.240 --> 00:02:55.170
Is that ok? Cause it takes a lot of energy
to pretend to be someone else, yeah? Which

00:02:55.170 --> 00:03:00.480
you have to when you're at work, yeah? So,
at least we have to. But I'm sure other people

00:03:00.480 --> 00:03:07.640
do. Yeah, so I got asked here, what I was
gonna do was just a small reading and then

00:03:07.640 --> 00:03:13.050
probably we could have some questions to talk
about some things. By way of introduction,

00:03:13.050 --> 00:03:20.210
I'm a writer and I'm really interested in
probably the dumbest thing you could be interested

00:03:20.210 --> 00:03:28.569
in if you're a writer. I'm like interested
in the gaps in stories, like the places where

00:03:28.569 --> 00:03:33.730
there isn't a story. Like, if someone misses
four or five, if there's like a four or five

00:03:33.730 --> 00:03:38.990
month gap in someone's life, that's what really
pulls me, yeah? If there's a period of history

00:03:38.990 --> 00:03:44.560
where there's no writing or there's no records
about it; I'm absolutely fascinated. So, it's

00:03:44.560 --> 00:03:48.920
like a bizarre thing because most writers
want to write about things where there's a

00:03:48.920 --> 00:03:54.071
least some documentation. So, in some way,
this book was--I wanted to write a book about,

00:03:54.071 --> 00:04:00.741
you're talking about the Galactus quote about
nameless lives. I wanted to write a book about

00:04:00.741 --> 00:04:05.200
this period in the island I came from, the
Dominican Republic, where everybody talks

00:04:05.200 --> 00:04:12.380
about this dictatorship, but nobody actually
says anything. It was like such a weird trauma

00:04:12.380 --> 00:04:16.530
that people would always say,"Oh, and the
time of Trujillo..." But then they won't actually

00:04:16.530 --> 00:04:22.510
say anything. There's no details. And I was
fascinated about how you can hide something

00:04:22.510 --> 00:04:28.340
in plain sight. It's like the dictatorship
is hidden in plain sight. Everybody mentions

00:04:28.340 --> 00:04:33.790
it, but nobody dares actually give any details
about it. And I started doing this about ten

00:04:33.790 --> 00:04:43.010
years ago because my grandfather, he's like
an old country guy, real funny dude. He belongs

00:04:43.010 --> 00:04:47.870
to that tradition, which he would like this,
because when he used to work in the Dominican

00:04:47.870 --> 00:04:52.940
Republic, they would have a lector, somebody
who would come and read while they were working.

00:04:52.940 --> 00:04:57.240
So, in his mind, this shit would be really
normal. He'd be like, "This is awesome!" Someone

00:04:57.240 --> 00:05:03.590
would always come in and usually read like
communist work, you know? And he told me this

00:05:03.590 --> 00:05:10.720
crazy story about during this dictatorship,
about how he was walking down the street and

00:05:10.720 --> 00:05:16.180
somebody was eating an orange and threw the
peel down. And at this time, they believed

00:05:16.180 --> 00:05:21.810
about 50% of the island were informants for
the dictatorship, which kinda makes East Germany

00:05:21.810 --> 00:05:28.980
look like normal. And somebody threw an orange
peel on the ground and the secret police came

00:05:28.980 --> 00:05:35.310
from all over and arrested the guy who threw
the orange peel and the three nearest people

00:05:35.310 --> 00:05:39.300
who didn't stopped and apprehend the guy who
threw the orange peel and my grandfather was

00:05:39.300 --> 00:05:45.370
number four. And so, the guy in front of him
was arrested and he was like, "Yeah, had I

00:05:45.370 --> 00:05:50.160
been walking any faster I'd have been in prison
for ten years for an orange." And he said

00:05:50.160 --> 00:05:56.160
this story and I have never, ever heard that
things were that crazy over there. So, part

00:05:56.160 --> 00:06:01.850
of this novel is about that, but part of it
is also about growing up in New Jersey, about

00:06:01.850 --> 00:06:07.940
kind of a big dork in New Jersey. Yeah, like
the huge nerds; '80s was like the perfect

00:06:07.940 --> 00:06:14.581
time for nerds, you know? It was like, personal
computing, role playing games; comic books

00:06:14.581 --> 00:06:20.560
became really big. And like video games, yeah?
It was all this perfect storm of nerdery,

00:06:20.560 --> 00:06:24.460
so I wanted to write about that. So, I'm just
gonna read a small, little piece and then

00:06:24.460 --> 00:06:31.000
maybe some questions or some comments and
then we can take it from there. All right?

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:36.330
The piece I'm gonna read is from, it's called
"Sentimental Education". There's like a lot

00:06:36.330 --> 00:06:42.710
of voices in this book cause it's-- I always
say, "Have you guys read A Wrinkle in Time?"

00:06:42.710 --> 00:06:47.870
Anybody read "Wrinkle in Time?" Poor Madeleine
L'Engle just died recently. Yeah, "Wrinkle

00:06:47.870 --> 00:06:51.650
in Time" was like, I loved that book. Do you
remember who the bad guy was in "Wrinkle in

00:06:51.650 --> 00:06:58.970
Time?" Does anybody remember that? C'mon,
man, the bad guy was called either "the enemy"

00:06:58.970 --> 00:07:04.800
or he was called "it". They were so afraid
to name him and anyway, for a kid who grew

00:07:04.800 --> 00:07:08.710
up in the shadow of a dictatorship, the "Wrinkle
in Time" really wigged me out because it was

00:07:08.710 --> 00:07:14.080
a dictatorship taken to the extreme. Cause
when the enemy had taken over a planet, do

00:07:14.080 --> 00:07:19.540
you remember what he did and how people acted?
Do you remember that all the kids would come

00:07:19.540 --> 00:07:24.890
out of their houses and bounce the basketball
at the same time? And I was like, "God." And

00:07:24.890 --> 00:07:30.230
I'd always-- for me, struck me, I was like,
"Fuck! That's a dictatorship gone nuts." So,

00:07:30.230 --> 00:07:33.960
there's all these voices in this book because
it's an attempt to get away from that single

00:07:33.960 --> 00:07:40.620
voice. And so, this is a kid talking about
his college life and how he meets, how he

00:07:40.620 --> 00:07:46.229
meets the-- the biggest nerd in the world.
But first, he meets his beautiful sister who

00:07:46.229 --> 00:07:52.419
he falls in love with. And so the voice is
kinda college-like, in Spanish would be a

00:07:52.419 --> 00:07:58.200
"sucio", I guess like a playboy. Dude's got
like, 25 girlfriends, yeah. So, it starts

00:07:58.200 --> 00:07:59.200
like this:

00:07:59.200 --> 00:08:00.780
[reads]

00:08:00.780 --> 00:08:02.740
"Sentimental Education: 1988-1992

00:08:02.740 --> 00:08:12.870
It started with me. The year before Oscar
fell; I'd suffered some nuttiness of my own.

00:08:12.870 --> 00:08:18.660
I got jumped as I was walking home from the
Roxy by this mess of New Brunswick townies;

00:08:18.660 --> 00:08:25.600
a bunch of funking morenos. Two AM and I was
on Joyce Kilmer Ave. For no good reason, alone

00:08:25.600 --> 00:08:31.840
and on foot. Why? Because I thought I was
hard; thought I would have no problems walking

00:08:31.840 --> 00:08:38.919
through the thicket of young dudes I saw on
the corner, which was a big mistake. I remember

00:08:38.919 --> 00:08:45.241
the smile on this one guys face the rest of
my fucking life, only second to his high school

00:08:45.241 --> 00:08:51.879
ring which plowed a nice furrow into my cheek.
Wish I could say I went down swinging, but

00:08:51.879 --> 00:08:58.339
these cats just laid me the fuck out. If it
hadn't been for some Samaritan driving by,

00:08:58.339 --> 00:09:03.230
the motherfuckers would probably have killed
me. The old guy who saved me wanted to take

00:09:03.230 --> 00:09:08.009
me to Robertwood Johnson, but I didn't have
any medical insurance and besides, ever since

00:09:08.009 --> 00:09:13.630
my brother had died of leukemia, I had not
been hot on doctors. So, of course, I was

00:09:13.630 --> 00:09:22.100
like, 'No, no, no.' And for having just gotten
my ass kicked, I actually felt pretty damn

00:09:22.100 --> 00:09:28.660
good. Until the next day when I felt like
I had died. So dizzy, I couldn't stand up

00:09:28.660 --> 00:09:33.869
without puking; my guts feeling like they'd
been taken out of me, beaten with mallets

00:09:33.869 --> 00:09:38.730
and then reattached with paper clips. It was
pretty bad and all the friends I had, all

00:09:38.730 --> 00:09:46.259
my great, wonderful boys, of all of them only
Lola came through. She heard about the beat

00:09:46.259 --> 00:09:53.959
down from my boy, Melvin, and shot over ASAP.
Never so happy to see someone my whole life.

00:09:53.959 --> 00:09:59.879
Lola, with her big, innocent teeth. Lola,
who actually cried when she saw the state

00:09:59.879 --> 00:10:06.149
I was in. She was the one who took care of
my sorry ass; who cooked and cleaned and picked

00:10:06.149 --> 00:10:11.910
up my class work, got me medicine and even
made sure that I showered. In other words,

00:10:11.910 --> 00:10:19.470
she sewed my balls back on and not any woman
can do that for a guy, you know? Believe you

00:10:19.470 --> 00:10:26.019
me, I could barely stand my head hurt so bad,
but she would wash my back and that was what

00:10:26.019 --> 00:10:33.319
I remembered the most about this mess. Her
hand on that sponge and that sponge on me.

00:10:33.319 --> 00:10:38.019
Even though I had a girlfriend, it was Lola
who spent those nights with me combing her

00:10:38.019 --> 00:10:45.889
hair out, once, twice, thrice before folding
her long self into bed next to me. 'No more

00:10:45.889 --> 00:10:53.009
night walking,' she said, 'Ok Mr. Kung Fu?'
At college, you're not supposed to care about

00:10:53.009 --> 00:10:59.110
anything. You're just supposed to fuck around
like crazy. But, believe it or not, I actually

00:10:59.110 --> 00:11:06.040
cared about Lola. She was a girl who was easy
to fall in love with. Lola, like the fucking

00:11:06.040 --> 00:11:12.360
opposite of the girls I usually went after.
Bitch was almost six feet tall and no chest

00:11:12.360 --> 00:11:18.850
at all and darker than your darkest grandmother
and she was like two girls in one: the skinniest

00:11:18.850 --> 00:11:26.399
upper body married to a pair of Cadillac hips
and an ill donkey. One of those over-achiever

00:11:26.399 --> 00:11:32.939
girls who runs all the organizations in college
and wears suits to student meetings. She was

00:11:32.939 --> 00:11:38.540
the president of her sorority, the head of
Salsa and co-chair of Take Back the Night

00:11:38.540 --> 00:11:45.869
and she spoke perfect, stuck-up Spanish. We'd
known each other since pre-freshman weekend,

00:11:45.869 --> 00:11:50.959
but it wasn't until a year later, till sophomore
year, when her mother got sick again that

00:11:50.959 --> 00:11:57.850
we had our little fling. 'Drive me home, Junot,'
was her opening line and a week later, things

00:11:57.850 --> 00:12:03.480
jumped off between us. I remember she was
wearing a pair of Douglas sweats and a tribe

00:12:03.480 --> 00:12:09.429
t-shirt. She took off the ring her boyfriend
had given her and then she kissed me. Her

00:12:09.429 --> 00:12:16.980
dark eyes never leaving mine. 'You have great
lips,' she said. And I ask you, how do you

00:12:16.980 --> 00:12:24.809
forget a girl like that? Only three nights
we were together before she got all guilty

00:12:24.809 --> 00:12:30.309
about her boyfriend and put an end to it.
And when Lola puts an end to something, she

00:12:30.309 --> 00:12:36.339
puts an end to it hard. Even those nights
after I got jumped, she wouldn't let me steal

00:12:36.339 --> 00:12:43.499
on her ass for nothing. 'So,' I said, 'you
can sleep in my bed, but you can't sleep with

00:12:43.499 --> 00:12:51.920
me?' And she laughed. 'Junot,' she said, 'yo
soy brierta pero yo no soy bruta.' Because

00:12:51.920 --> 00:12:59.279
she knew exactly what kind of sucio I was.
Two days after we kind of broke up, she saw

00:12:59.279 --> 00:13:07.600
me hitting on one of her line sisters at a
party and she turned her long back on me."

00:13:07.600 --> 00:13:16.720
So, that's it. It's just a small entry, yeah?
So, I think the best thing to do is to read

00:13:16.720 --> 00:13:21.190
a little bit, yeah? And then maybe take some
questions and I'll just finish off by reading

00:13:21.190 --> 00:13:28.889
something else. Or comments, yeah? You guys
can't be any harder or meaner than my kids,

00:13:28.889 --> 00:13:35.649
so I figured anything you wanted to say or
talk about, that'd be cool. It spares you

00:13:35.649 --> 00:13:41.540
having to listen to me for another 15 minutes
of reading. So, we can save that for the end.

00:13:41.540 --> 00:13:42.540
Yeah?

00:13:42.540 --> 00:13:43.540
