00:14:02.629 --> 00:14:03.629
&gt;&gt;Diaz: Hi.

00:14:03.629 --> 00:14:06.569
&gt;&gt;member #1: Just a quick question, I understand
that this is your first novel, but you've

00:14:06.569 --> 00:14:12.259
written fiction for The New Yorker. What inspired
you to, at this point in your life, to take

00:14:12.259 --> 00:14:16.240
this leap into writing a novel and this novel?

00:14:16.240 --> 00:14:21.690
&gt;&gt;Diaz: That's a good question. I always was
a, I come from this immigrant, over-achiever

00:14:21.690 --> 00:14:28.029
family, my family--you know when you're a
kid and you score well at anything? In my

00:14:28.029 --> 00:14:32.940
family, they were so fucking excited. They
were like, "We got one." You know? They were

00:14:32.940 --> 00:14:36.439
like, "Ah, he's gonna be a doctor, he's gonna
be a scientist, he's gonna be whatever." And

00:14:36.439 --> 00:14:39.949
so, I was like really good at scoring those
damn tests that they give you as a kid. I

00:14:39.949 --> 00:14:45.899
was always scoring like the 99th percentile
at those stupid, little tests, but I loved

00:14:45.899 --> 00:14:51.790
to read. And I kind of screwed my poor parents
who wanted something more professional and

00:14:51.790 --> 00:14:57.410
I became an artist. I wanted to, I loved to
read and I wanted to be a writer like, probably

00:14:57.410 --> 00:15:02.999
since I got into high school, I thought writing
would be cool 'cause I liked to read so much

00:15:02.999 --> 00:15:08.279
and it was also kinda reacting to my old man.
My old man was like a military guy, he was

00:15:08.279 --> 00:15:13.820
like a boxer. It was like, he got a black
belt in Judo. Every Sunday, the pain in the

00:15:13.820 --> 00:15:18.279
ass would go take us to the rifle range, you
know? And I was like, I didn't want to be

00:15:18.279 --> 00:15:22.350
anything that he kind of approved of in a
weird way. And so, being a writer seemed like

00:15:22.350 --> 00:15:28.089
a cool thing to do and I got pretty serious
about it 'cause, despite how much I wanna

00:15:28.089 --> 00:15:32.959
resist my parents, you have that immigrant
work ethic where if you don't have three jobs

00:15:32.959 --> 00:15:39.720
you're lazy. My mom would be like, 10 p.m.,
she's like "Why aren't you at work?" And the

00:15:39.720 --> 00:15:43.609
commercial would be on, "Do you know where
your children are?" My mom was like, "Oh,

00:15:43.609 --> 00:15:44.930
you better be working."

00:15:44.930 --> 00:15:45.930
[laughter]

00:15:45.930 --> 00:15:52.720
So, probably from about college, I started
bringing that weird work ethic into writing

00:15:52.720 --> 00:15:58.679
and I'd been writing for awhile. It's just
that the two books I published were the only

00:15:58.679 --> 00:16:03.869
ones that worked. I had written like, three
other books, but they were like really, really

00:16:03.869 --> 00:16:09.689
bad. So, it's like, I'm telling you, if any
of you guys ever want to be artists, I'm a

00:16:09.689 --> 00:16:11.570
perfect encouragement. You can't be farther
worse than me.

00:16:11.570 --> 00:16:13.059
[laughter]

00:16:13.059 --> 00:16:19.179
It's like, three for two-- that's bad, guys.
So, it was a lot of that, but I think like

00:16:19.179 --> 00:16:23.459
more fundamentally, growing up, I mean, I'm
older than most of you guys here. It's like

00:16:23.459 --> 00:16:27.720
you guys look like babies to me some of ya'll,
you know? Like, little. But I grew up in the

00:16:27.720 --> 00:16:33.350
'80s, yeah? And it was like a weird time to
be poor and Dominican and immigrant cause

00:16:33.350 --> 00:16:40.999
the '80s was like, it was crack, it was AIDS,
it was genocidal wars in Central America,

00:16:40.999 --> 00:16:45.720
it was voodoo economics, where basically,
that was when they say, "We take all the money

00:16:45.720 --> 00:16:50.009
out of the system and we give it to the rich.
We promise you, it'll trickle down to the

00:16:50.009 --> 00:16:55.009
poor." Which, of course, didn't work at all.
And so, all these things were happening and

00:16:55.009 --> 00:16:58.689
as a kid, I was really observant and there
was a part of me that felt that there was

00:16:58.689 --> 00:17:03.929
this vacuum in the historical record. I would
turn on the TV and all these things that I

00:17:03.929 --> 00:17:08.740
saw happening at once, nobody was talking
about. And so, of course, there was this desire

00:17:08.740 --> 00:17:14.411
to bear witness. It sounds like kind of lofty,
but as a kid I really did want, I felt like

00:17:14.411 --> 00:17:18.870
I was seeing shit that nobody wanted to talk
about. And there was this desire in me to

00:17:18.870 --> 00:17:23.800
know that and that was part of my writing.
I mean, first, all I ever wrote were like

00:17:23.800 --> 00:17:28.380
kinda news reports from my neighborhood; all
the shit that was happening that nobody would

00:17:28.380 --> 00:17:37.810
ever care about. It was really weird. So,
I think that was some of it. Yeah. Oh, Lord.

