on what you've said, what I'm reading here

00:17:47.370 --> 00:17:52.910
is has like, college in New Jersey. Well,
can you describe the relationship between

00:17:52.910 --> 00:17:57.660
the Trujillo regime and what's the link between
that and this story.

00:17:57.660 --> 00:18:01.330
&gt;&gt;Diaz: Yeah, no that's an excellent question
like just from what I was talking about. I

00:18:01.330 --> 00:18:05.520
was talking about a dictatorship and yet the
first thing I read to you is a story about

00:18:05.520 --> 00:18:11.600
being at Rutgers; just running around chasing
chicks. And the real question is that what

00:18:11.600 --> 00:18:17.072
happens when you're a kid like me, who goes
to Rutgers and basically runs around and chase

00:18:17.072 --> 00:18:23.001
chicks and you're, you visit a home where
your parents were like victims of a dictatorship.

00:18:23.001 --> 00:18:32.630
Do those histories ever meet and do they actually
ever influence each other? Does one speak

00:18:32.630 --> 00:18:36.910
to the other? Does the fact that I had all
this access to all this privilege-- and I

00:18:36.910 --> 00:18:40.311
thought it was incredible privilege being
at a state school and learning all this stuff--

00:18:40.311 --> 00:18:46.440
did that impact my mom at all? And did the
sorta silence around her personal history

00:18:46.440 --> 00:18:52.370
did that have any influence on me? And in
some ways the book is about, I thought, was

00:18:52.370 --> 00:18:59.350
about the tyranny of the present. How the
present is such a strong force that it's very

00:18:59.350 --> 00:19:04.630
hard to think about the past. It's a lot of
historians talk about this term, "the tyranny

00:19:04.630 --> 00:19:09.780
of the present," that it's like the present
is such a force that people don't even wanna

00:19:09.780 --> 00:19:14.230
see old movies; they'd rather see a remake
because they're like, "I don't want really

00:19:14.230 --> 00:19:19.870
to do anything with history. I don't want
to think about the past." And the problem

00:19:19.870 --> 00:19:26.650
is that it's, we live not only in the present,
we also live in a historical moment. A lot

00:19:26.650 --> 00:19:30.430
of the things that have happened in the past
have very subtle influences on our choices

00:19:30.430 --> 00:19:36.250
and our decisions and part of what the book
was about was trying to run these two stories

00:19:36.250 --> 00:19:41.910
side by side and see if there was anything
that was happening between the two of them.

00:19:41.910 --> 00:19:48.970
Is it true that I always felt that even though
I was living in a real contemporary, Jersey,

00:19:48.970 --> 00:19:55.020
into baseball, into hip-hop, I always felt
the shadow of that past history; it was on

00:19:55.020 --> 00:20:01.130
us? Even though none of my siblings believed
it was. And yet, all of my siblings act the

00:20:01.130 --> 00:20:06.670
same way in some ways. I mean, you wouldn't
have to be a super smart person to figure

00:20:06.670 --> 00:20:14.070
out that all of us are the children of victims
of a dictatorship. It's like, kids who grew

00:20:14.070 --> 00:20:21.430
up in Jersey who seem completely normal, they
never speak in public. It's like my parent's

00:20:21.430 --> 00:20:29.070
ability to not to say anything incriminating.
Anybody calls the house, it's like nobody's

00:20:29.070 --> 00:20:33.730
ever home and you've got the wrong house.
When I got accepted to Cornell, it took them

00:20:33.730 --> 00:20:39.200
months to track me down because my mother
was like, "Who? Junot? No, he doesn't live

00:20:39.200 --> 00:20:40.200
here." Click.

00:20:40.200 --> 00:20:41.640
[laughter]

00:20:41.640 --> 00:20:46.910
And so, it seems really minor, but I do think
that there's a tremendous amount of history

00:20:46.910 --> 00:20:54.270
that bleeds into the present and has an influence
on us that we don't even understand. And so

00:20:54.270 --> 00:20:58.073
for me, I guess that was the point of the
question. How much of the present, or what

00:20:58.073 --> 00:21:04.780
we call the present, is made up of the past?
And even at an unconscious level, are we influenced

00:21:04.780 --> 00:21:09.240
by-- they talk about the unconscious, it's
like when somebody is cheating on you and

00:21:09.240 --> 00:21:15.880
you don't know it; your kinda unconscious
knows it. And they say that that's like real

00:21:15.880 --> 00:21:20.220
common for people's unconscious to know that
somebody's betraying them and their conscious

00:21:20.220 --> 00:21:29.700
not to know. And so I've always wondered how
that works. And I was very, very curious about

00:21:29.700 --> 00:21:36.640
the link between a pair of parents who grew
up disciplined in a dictatorship and then

00:21:36.640 --> 00:21:43.860
how do they raise their kids in their own
house? And yet, you know Rutgers? It seems

00:21:43.860 --> 00:21:49.900
so far away. When I was at Rutgers dancing
salsa, Santa Domingo and Secret Police, that

00:21:49.900 --> 00:21:55.460
seemed a million miles away. And yet, I would
go home and see my mom and my mom's back would

00:21:55.460 --> 00:22:01.360
be all scarred and it would suddenly be right
there. And I was like, "Hmmm. Is it just that

00:22:01.360 --> 00:22:06.810
I'm pretending that the history's not here?
Or is it really here? We're making it all

00:22:06.810 --> 00:22:12.680
up." And I'm not sure that the answer is more
about putting these pieces together and seeing

00:22:12.680 --> 00:22:17.600
if I could generate any conversation. Sir?

00:22:17.600 --> 00:22:23.960
&gt;&gt;member #3: Yeah, I had a question. The first
