00:23:11.350 --> 00:23:18.120
McSweeney's meets Cosmopolitan comics are
a high art thing? That seems to be a lot about

00:23:18.120 --> 00:23:21.480
upper middle-class white dudes talking about
it and just how your book fits into that.

00:23:21.480 --> 00:23:26.620
&gt;&gt;Diaz: Hmm. That's in interesting question.
Look, it's, part of this whole thing-- it's

00:23:26.620 --> 00:23:32.060
only because the market is rewarding it that
you suddenly see all these "the white guys

00:23:32.060 --> 00:23:37.610
suddenly talking about comic books and stuff."
I mean, there's been white guys reading comic

00:23:37.610 --> 00:23:42.430
books for a zillion years, but it's only now
the market's beginning to reward those kind

00:23:42.430 --> 00:23:50.010
of books. For me, the real question isn't
about whether, the real question is that it

00:23:50.010 --> 00:23:57.400
seems that the relationship between high literary
figures and, let's say, comics is unidirectional.

00:23:57.400 --> 00:24:02.800
So that Michael Chabon and Lethem can turn
around and they're literary figures even though

00:24:02.800 --> 00:24:08.410
Lethem started in a genre. He started as a
really cool science fiction writer. They can

00:24:08.410 --> 00:24:14.100
go and write comic books, but it's sorta like
going slumming; they can always come home

00:24:14.100 --> 00:24:18.970
to that really great suburb called Literary
Fiction. So, they can go dance with the black

00:24:18.970 --> 00:24:24.760
girls down in Darkie Town and come back and
they still got their really nice zip code.

00:24:24.760 --> 00:24:31.130
And my thing is that I feel like things will
change when Michael Chabon is losing a Pulitzer

00:24:31.130 --> 00:24:38.710
Prize to the comic book writer of Spiderman.
In other words, it's like the literary figures

00:24:38.710 --> 00:24:43.140
can go loot the genres all they want, but
they never have to worry about the people

00:24:43.140 --> 00:24:48.180
who are actually genre-practitioners challenging
their literary prerogatives so that the borrowing

00:24:48.180 --> 00:24:53.660
is unidirectional. I don't know if that makes
any sense. I seem like I sound like I'm crazy.

00:24:53.660 --> 00:24:57.860
But it's sorta like having an American passport
versus having a Third World passport. I feel

00:24:57.860 --> 00:25:02.730
like the genres, they have passports from
like, North Korea. So, you're not allowed

00:25:02.730 --> 00:25:08.720
anywhere. Oh, American Academy of Arts? Sorry,
fool! You write what? Hulk? Nope.

00:25:08.720 --> 00:25:09.720
[laughter]

00:25:09.720 --> 00:25:13.350
But Michael Chabon can turn around and write
a Hulk novel and it'd be the best selling

00:25:13.350 --> 00:25:19.050
thing. And he'll be like everywhere. And for
me, as a writer of color, one of what it did,

00:25:19.050 --> 00:25:22.640
what's interesting is that in the United States,
if you're a writer of color, no matter what

00:25:22.640 --> 00:25:29.610
you write about, you're considered a genre
anyway. You're never accepted in a real literary--

00:25:29.610 --> 00:25:33.370
you know, there's always this bizarre question.
I went to do a book signing earlier and the

00:25:33.370 --> 00:25:37.040
owner of the bookstore said, "Hey, I heard
if you don't speak Spanish you can actually

00:25:37.040 --> 00:25:43.340
read your book." I'm like, "Well, it's in
English, so I'm assuming you can fucking read

00:25:43.340 --> 00:25:44.340
the book."

00:25:44.340 --> 00:25:45.340
[laughter]

00:25:45.340 --> 00:25:51.080
I'm just like, Jesus, I wonder how many people
who are like--anyway. So, there's this sense

00:25:51.080 --> 00:25:57.600
that part of the joke for me was that being
a writer of color, you're already considered

00:25:57.600 --> 00:26:02.330
as bizarrely marginalized. Your passport is
always being checked three times before you

00:26:02.330 --> 00:26:06.030
get let in. You'll get let in, but boy oh
boy, they'll run you through security for

00:26:06.030 --> 00:26:13.740
20 minutes. And so, I felt part of the joke
was I can't decide who's more of a genre in

00:26:13.740 --> 00:26:19.010
this book. The parts about the Dominican Republic
and the parts about being a Dominican kid

00:26:19.010 --> 00:26:24.640
at Rutgers, or the parts about the science
fiction comic books? Like who gets the better

00:26:24.640 --> 00:26:29.330
passport? In fact, I feel like if you're a
Dominican writer in the United States, you

00:26:29.330 --> 00:26:35.500
have a lot more in common with somebody writing
The Hulk than Michael Chabon has in common

00:26:35.500 --> 00:26:40.460
with anybody writing Superman. Because, in
the end, both me and the comic book guy, we

00:26:40.460 --> 00:26:46.550
go back to our crappy ass neighborhoods; sorta
the neighborhoods where you fit in the art.

00:26:46.550 --> 00:26:51.580
I mean, these are like generalizations, which,
again, if we had more time there's way more

00:26:51.580 --> 00:26:56.621
nuanced ways to talk about this, but it's
always like when you only have 30 minutes

00:26:56.621 --> 00:27:01.900
to talk, you end up having to try to get your
ideas across in the brute and never in the

00:27:01.900 --> 00:27:07.240
way that they really deserve to be crossed.
So, in my mind, I always was working in that

00:27:07.240 --> 00:27:11.520
joke. I always felt so separated from all
those dudes who were doing it and were gonna

00:27:11.520 --> 00:27:18.920
win the awards because I just felt like, historically,
writers of color in the United States have

00:27:18.920 --> 00:27:24.801
been even more marginalized than comic book
writers. I mean, I think about Joseph Campbell,

00:27:24.801 --> 00:27:34.570
No, excuse me, I think about that-- Joseph
Campbell. God, I don't know why it's flying

00:27:34.570 --> 00:27:38.520
out of my name because remember the name of
the science fiction editor who basically put

00:27:38.520 --> 00:27:45.170
together the Silver Age Science Fiction? His
last name was Campbell, too. Anyway, he didn't

00:27:45.170 --> 00:27:50.030
allow no black writers, Latino writers or
women. He refused to publish them. And if

00:27:50.030 --> 00:27:57.111
anyone wrote about a black character, he would
reject it. And so, for 40 years all of the

00:27:57.111 --> 00:28:01.710
main science fiction organs refused to publish
work by anybody of color or who had people

00:28:01.710 --> 00:28:08.360
of color in them. This was up to the '70s.
So, I really was interested in that question

00:28:08.360 --> 00:28:16.020
as I was writing. It's like, which is more
weird? So, yeah. Madam?

00:28:16.020 --> 00:28:19.970
