00:29:03.990 --> 00:29:07.840
resist that characterization? Is that something
you find kind of offensive? Or, how do you

00:29:07.840 --> 00:29:12.050
feel about that? And if that's something you
don't like, how do you combat that and say,

00:29:12.050 --> 00:29:17.870
"This is a book that I've written. Take it
for its merit."

00:29:17.870 --> 00:29:23.140
I'm not suddenly representing all the Dominicans
in the US or abroad or whatnot.

00:29:23.140 --> 00:29:27.330
&gt;&gt;Diaz: Thank you. It's a really good question.
Yeah, I mean, it's the weirdest thing. One

00:29:27.330 --> 00:29:30.880
of the things again, these are issues which
people tend to be not so comfortable about,

00:29:30.880 --> 00:29:36.370
but it's kind of bizarre, man, that if you're
a writer of color in the United States you're

00:29:36.370 --> 00:29:44.150
always viewed as a collective. In other words,
you're viewed as somehow an ambassador from

00:29:44.150 --> 00:29:49.309
this larger collective. But it's at every
level, at a societal level. You'll even see

00:29:49.309 --> 00:29:54.480
it amongst ourselves. I mean, how many people
will tell me they won't date--, an entire

00:29:54.480 --> 00:29:59.670
group of guys-- but always that group of guys
tends to be ethnic. It's like, you're much

00:29:59.670 --> 00:30:04.830
more likely to collectivize an ethnic group
cause assume they all share something really

00:30:04.830 --> 00:30:10.020
deeply in common. And I think that it's something
that is part of the condition that we're dealing

00:30:10.020 --> 00:30:16.400
with. It's like, trying to be simultaneously
viewed as someone who belongs to a community,

00:30:16.400 --> 00:30:22.350
but also an individual, that's a really good
thing, but most of us are usually viewed just

00:30:22.350 --> 00:30:29.809
as a part of a collective. And I am no more
the representative and the spokesperson for

00:30:29.809 --> 00:30:34.610
the Dominican community as I am to the New
Jersey community. I mean, if you wanna understand

00:30:34.610 --> 00:30:38.110
what the Dominican community is, you would
need about ten million novels and then you

00:30:38.110 --> 00:30:47.490
would only have the first pass. And I do think
that it's, there's a deep desire in American

00:30:47.490 --> 00:30:53.200
culture to have native informants; to have
people who are gonna translate something for

00:30:53.200 --> 00:30:58.860
you. Because it's far easier to have a native
informant explaining to you a larger culture

00:30:58.860 --> 00:31:05.380
than it is for you to encounter the stupendous
complexity and diversity of that culture.

00:31:05.380 --> 00:31:11.420
Like, it's so much nicer to boil down Japan
down to your one JA friend you know and that

00:31:11.420 --> 00:31:14.990
dude probably doesn't like rice. But you're
like, "Yeah, that's Japanese culture."

00:31:14.990 --> 00:31:15.990
[laughter]

00:31:15.990 --> 00:31:17.980
And everyone in Japan, you're like, "Yeah,
yeah, he knows."

00:31:17.980 --> 00:31:19.350
[laughter]

00:31:19.350 --> 00:31:25.140
And a lot of us fall into that because it,
it, it's also a weird, we become complicitive

00:31:25.140 --> 00:31:29.510
in that. Cause I have a lot of friends of
mine who, they're like the expert in all things

00:31:29.510 --> 00:31:36.150
Korean. I'm like, "Motherfucking, you never
been to Korea. How did you get an expert in

00:31:36.150 --> 00:31:41.670
this?" 'Cause his parents are Korean, so I
feel it's, there's a double-sided, as in.

00:31:41.670 --> 00:31:48.300
As a writer, as an artist, what really matters
to me is that a piece of art is really, in

00:31:48.300 --> 00:31:55.750
some ways, a distillation of a single subjectivity
interacting with usually a very random and

00:31:55.750 --> 00:32:02.340
bizarre collective. And if you get the proportion
wrong, you in some way erase what's important

00:32:02.340 --> 00:32:07.300
about a piece of work. If you see a piece
of work only as an example of a larger collective,

00:32:07.300 --> 00:32:12.760
you've erased that person, that individual
arches and whirls of the thumbprint of the

00:32:12.760 --> 00:32:18.050
artist who made it. But if you reduce someone
just as the individual, you lose the fact

00:32:18.050 --> 00:32:25.880
that this person came about in a context,
yeah? It's like, Picasso doesn't make sense,

00:32:25.880 --> 00:32:30.580
he does not make sense if you don't understand
the context he came out of. There's no way

00:32:30.580 --> 00:32:35.640
an individual makes sense without their context
'cause usually you're reacting and interacting

00:32:35.640 --> 00:32:42.150
to it somehow. So, I think that both elements
are vitally important and often the stress

00:32:42.150 --> 00:32:47.970
is put on you to be, as a writer of color,
as an artist of color, more towards your collective.

00:32:47.970 --> 00:32:52.010
But then we take it too far sometimes where
some writers of color are like, "I am the

00:32:52.010 --> 00:32:57.860
supreme individual. I want nothing to do with
my community." And that's equally toxic and,

00:32:57.860 --> 00:33:03.230
I think, misleading. And it's the hardest
thing for all of us is equilibrium.

00:33:03.230 --> 00:33:12.850
I know the gap while we get to the microphone.

00:33:12.850 --> 00:33:19.100
I have like, the whitest shoelaces. I'm like,
in envy of you.

00:33:19.100 --> 00:33:20.100
[laughter]

00:33:20.100 --> 00:33:22.370
It rocks, man.

