00:34:11.099 --> 00:34:16.669
&gt;&gt;Diaz: Cool. Thank you. I have this bizarre
thing with language. It's like, typical immigrant,

00:34:16.669 --> 00:34:20.740
you come and you have to learn the damn language
and all my siblings learned it within six

00:34:20.740 --> 00:34:26.319
months and I had to get put in Special Education
because I couldn't speak it. For some reason,

00:34:26.319 --> 00:34:31.109
English wouldn't come out of my mouth. And
I learned to read English within a few months,

00:34:31.109 --> 00:34:37.700
but I couldn't speak it for a very long time.
So, language has always been tricky in some

00:34:37.700 --> 00:34:42.740
ways and then typical adolescent reaction,
you're like, you get that weird self-hate

00:34:42.740 --> 00:34:46.700
period where you hate everything that has
to do with your larger culture. So, I almost

00:34:46.700 --> 00:34:53.099
lost all my Spanish in my teens and then I
had to relearn it all. And the thing with

00:34:53.099 --> 00:34:59.250
me is not so much that I have either a Spanish
or an English voice, it's more that I have

00:34:59.250 --> 00:35:04.869
those two voices running through my head at
the same time. And sometimes, I'm in my English

00:35:04.869 --> 00:35:10.440
self, my English dominant self in a complete
Spanish setting. And so, people are speaking

00:35:10.440 --> 00:35:14.971
in Spanish and I'm translating the Spanish
from my English self. And sometimes, I'm in

00:35:14.971 --> 00:35:19.819
my Spanish dominant self in an English setting
and I'm sitting there listening to everybody

00:35:19.819 --> 00:35:25.239
speaking English and I'm just like, "Oh, brother."
And I'm translating the English to my Spanish

00:35:25.239 --> 00:35:32.359
self and the best parts are when my languages
actually coincide. 'Cause it's just whatever

00:35:32.359 --> 00:35:36.559
frame of mind you're in and sometimes you
encounter these worlds. And for me, it's like

00:35:36.559 --> 00:35:43.609
I feel both languages are running simultaneously
and they'll cross at weird moments and when

00:35:43.609 --> 00:35:48.000
I'm writing, I tend to have both of them running
through my head and the one that bullies through

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:54.541
the most, because English is what I write
in, but Spanish and English are what I think

00:35:54.541 --> 00:36:00.040
and speak in. And so, in my head, Spanish
will always like seize control. It's like

00:36:00.040 --> 00:36:05.520
the really angry driver, like passenger, who
grabs the wheel. So, anytime I'm writing in

00:36:05.520 --> 00:36:12.050
English and Spanish is like, "Enough!" Yeah,
[speaking in Spanish] Suddenly, it just, it

00:36:12.050 --> 00:36:17.750
comes in. But it's also a process of rewriting.
I don't want you to think that it's completely

00:36:17.750 --> 00:36:23.480
this intuitive bizarre relationship to the
linguistics. When you're rewriting, different

00:36:23.480 --> 00:36:27.820
languages begin to help out. Sometimes, I'll
be reading a sentence in English and it's

00:36:27.820 --> 00:36:31.490
not until I read it from the Spanish frame
of mind that I'll understand the way the sentence

00:36:31.490 --> 00:36:36.839
works. So, a lot of times I'm doing all of
that and teaching at MIT is really great.

00:36:36.839 --> 00:36:40.241
I mean, I dunno guys, being an artist-- to
