00:37:03.090 --> 00:37:10.180
people who, they tend to be like anyone who's
superlative. You've basically sacrificed a

00:37:10.180 --> 00:37:15.210
huge chunk of your childhood to get to this
place, but you didn't get to MIT because you

00:37:15.210 --> 00:37:18.650
went, you got drunk two nights in a row. That
didn't fuckin happen.

00:37:18.650 --> 00:37:19.650
[laughter]

00:37:19.650 --> 00:37:23.010
You know what I'm saying? You didn't do what
I did when I was in high school and got into

00:37:23.010 --> 00:37:29.619
MIT. You didn't skip a week of school to watch
the play-offs. Like, that just didn't happen.

00:37:29.619 --> 00:37:34.789
These kids sacrifice an enormous amount of
their childhoods just to get there and so,

00:37:34.789 --> 00:37:39.710
part of what's really cool about it is you're
teaching what everybody teaches at a university.

00:37:39.710 --> 00:37:43.369
It's how to be more critical minded. Beyond
just the subject you're teaching, if you're

00:37:43.369 --> 00:37:47.160
teaching literature, if you're teaching high
energy physics, you're also teaching that

00:37:47.160 --> 00:37:52.059
component of how to be critical minded. But
the second thing at a place like MIT what

00:37:52.059 --> 00:37:58.650
you're teaching is compassion. It sounds really
like kissy smoochy softy, but those kids have

00:37:58.650 --> 00:38:03.700
like, no compassion. You didn't get into a
top select college because you were a compassionate

00:38:03.700 --> 00:38:09.829
person. You're like, "Oh, you failed. I forgive
you." That wasn't you. You got in there because

00:38:09.829 --> 00:38:11.529
you got a B. "You fucking suck!"

00:38:11.529 --> 00:38:13.150
[laughter]

00:38:13.150 --> 00:38:18.119
And so, one of the weirdest things that I
learned at MIT was that, beyond just teaching

00:38:18.119 --> 00:38:23.759
them what I had to teach them, compassion,
which I normally never thought about I had

00:38:23.759 --> 00:38:28.059
to learn how to teach it. Because I would
have kids who, if they would make one error,

00:38:28.059 --> 00:38:33.661
they would just be like, you know? I would
be like, "Whoa." You know as an artist, you

00:38:33.661 --> 00:38:41.730
know that errors are the fountain of your
inspiration. It's completely unlike the academic

00:38:41.730 --> 00:38:46.309
process. In an academic process, if you make
a mistake, you're punished whether it's through

00:38:46.309 --> 00:38:51.509
low grade or through, "You don't get the little
golden sticker." But as an artist, your mistakes,

00:38:51.509 --> 00:38:57.390
that's the foundation of your work because
you can't explore without making mistakes

00:38:57.390 --> 00:39:03.119
and exploration is the root of all artistic
endeavor. You're taking chances and you're

00:39:03.119 --> 00:39:06.339
messing things up. And you mess things up
and that leads you into another direction.

00:39:06.339 --> 00:39:13.509
But in an academic setting, too many mistakes
and you're getting kicked the fuck out. And

00:39:13.509 --> 00:39:19.470
so, it's this weird thing that you're involved
with as a teacher. You're involved with attempting

00:39:19.470 --> 00:39:24.400
to make the student know the material, make
them more critical minded, this other aspect,

00:39:24.400 --> 00:39:30.099
which is compassion and then trying to teach
the ethos of exploration, which is quite different

00:39:30.099 --> 00:39:36.079
from the ethos of approval. Exploration and
approval tend to be two entirely different

00:39:36.079 --> 00:39:43.881
things. So, there's one more question, yeah?
Or, someone, anyone? Sir?

00:39:43.881 --> 00:39:55.259
You guys are so good, I'm telling you. In
