00:39:58.700 --> 00:40:03.869
&gt;&gt;man #4: You touched earlier on this issue
of high culture and low culture with the literary

00:40:03.869 --> 00:40:08.470
fiction writers kinda adopting comic books.
So, I wonder if you could speak to, I don't

00:40:08.470 --> 00:40:13.690
know what the academic perception for your
work or other similar work has been, but I

00:40:13.690 --> 00:40:18.201
wonder if you could speak to the role of the
academy and disseminating this culture and

00:40:18.201 --> 00:40:21.700
what you think it's doing to it? It's sort
of the problem with the Ivory Tower, I guess.

00:40:21.700 --> 00:40:26.710
&gt;&gt;Diaz: Yeah, no, that's a really nice question.
I'm, again, my awareness is really limited.

00:40:26.710 --> 00:40:32.670
There's people who study academia as a subject,
like what's happening at the select colleges,

00:40:32.670 --> 00:40:37.460
what's happening at the university press level,
what's happening at the level of the people

00:40:37.460 --> 00:40:41.430
who are getting tenure. And those people tend
to have a much more holistic longitudinal

00:40:41.430 --> 00:40:45.700
view of what's going on. So, what I'm gonna
tell you now is completely provisional, episodic

00:40:45.700 --> 00:40:54.950
and reveals more of my narrow, my narrow exposure
of than probably any real significant knowledge.

00:40:54.950 --> 00:41:08.030
My sense is always that there's a real tension
between readers-- those of us who love to

00:41:08.030 --> 00:41:16.420
read-- and the rest of the critical apparatus.
So that like, readers are a really big part

00:41:16.420 --> 00:41:25.249
of what makes this business roll; people who
just love to read. And reading is deeply anti-heirarchical.

00:41:25.249 --> 00:41:30.279
If you've ever met a reader, their bookshelves
tend to be wild. They tend to be like, "Yep,

00:41:30.279 --> 00:41:38.670
they've got Jude Deveraux right next to William
Gaddis." Or, they'll read like Drizzt, the

00:41:38.670 --> 00:41:45.660
crazy, dark elf, Dungeons and Dragons character
dude who has like, 80 novels. And the same,

00:41:45.660 --> 00:41:51.039
these same people will talk to you all fuckin
day about how important Tony Morrison is.

00:41:51.039 --> 00:41:56.079
Readers are very, very creolized in a way
that's kind of interesting. And the problem

00:41:56.079 --> 00:42:02.059
with academy is not the problem, but its structural
limitation is that it has to create categories,

00:42:02.059 --> 00:42:08.440
it has to create canons and it has to create
hierarchy. There's only so much time in a

00:42:08.440 --> 00:42:15.990
class you have to study. And I feel like in
there there's already an implicit, an implicit

00:42:15.990 --> 00:42:23.479
opposition so, in a way, I'm always writing
for readers. Cause readers, I feel, are far

00:42:23.479 --> 00:42:29.279
more generous and far more likely to understand
that your work isn't always there for you

00:42:29.279 --> 00:42:35.529
just to give it a decimal point value to it.
It's like, the love you have for a piece of

00:42:35.529 --> 00:42:43.650
crap literature, is it more or less than the
love you have for Dickens? And can you tell?

00:42:43.650 --> 00:42:48.690
That's what readers are about. They have this
love that's really hard to quantify and the

00:42:48.690 --> 00:42:53.069
thing with canonical work is that it's, I
mean, the thing with academic work is that

00:42:53.069 --> 00:42:58.569
if you're a person that your work is being
picked up for dissertations, that you're work

00:42:58.569 --> 00:43:06.410
is interesting for the current theoretical
apparatus, it's all good. If you're outside

00:43:06.410 --> 00:43:17.249
of that purvey, it can be problematic. And
so, there's a sense in my mind that you're

00:43:17.249 --> 00:43:21.979
really dealing with two kinds of legacies.
You're dealing with your legacy among readers

00:43:21.979 --> 00:43:26.900
and you're dealing with your critical legacy.
And both of them are dynamic, both of them

00:43:26.900 --> 00:43:32.589
are changeable, both of them are hard to predict
where they're coming from and I'm always way

00:43:32.589 --> 00:43:40.059
more scared of the, I'm always way more scared
of the academic one. Not just because it's

00:43:40.059 --> 00:43:45.529
some anti-intellectual streak in me, is that
there's so much at stake in academia. There's

00:43:45.529 --> 00:43:49.829
tenure, there's your relationship with your
professor, what you're getting published,

00:43:49.829 --> 00:43:57.670
what's the current critical climate. While
readers tend not to have any of those considerations.

00:43:57.670 --> 00:44:04.089
They tend to be reading far more freely and
far more unencumbered. And so, currently,

00:44:04.089 --> 00:44:09.990
I'm like, as a writer, I could have a dozen
people writing dissertations on you, but it

00:44:09.990 --> 00:44:16.160
doesn't mean much other than that you're just,
you're fitting, you're fitting the profile

00:44:16.160 --> 00:44:24.249
of what the critics need right now. And yet,
if you're not read, it doesn't mean, either

00:44:24.249 --> 00:44:30.160
because most writers are writing for a future
audience. Few writers are writing for an audience

00:44:30.160 --> 00:44:34.869
that's here now. Most of us are waiting for
an audience to assemble itself that can really

00:44:34.869 --> 00:44:40.180
interact with you. And so, I think they're
both kind of sketchy, but I also don't want

00:44:40.180 --> 00:44:43.729
anyone to get a sense that either one of them
is quite evil. I think they just have their

00:44:43.729 --> 00:44:49.509
advantages and disadvantages. But again, both
the academic and the standard reading audience

00:44:49.509 --> 00:44:55.479
are provisional. And as an artist, you're
trying to engage, you're trying to engage

00:44:55.479 --> 00:45:01.339
a kind of a collective over a long term in
an unpredictable way. And neither of those

00:45:01.339 --> 00:45:08.220
can really predict where your work is gonna
end up. So, guys, I thought I would just end,

